  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Detrending: \n",
    "In practice, process test data often contain low frequency drift that is induced by unknown disturbances. These low frequency disturbances will create negative impacts on identification and has to be eliminated.\n",
    "\n",
    "The pre-process of data with detrending will estimate the trend signal and remove it from the measurements. There are many different trend signals, such as Mean, Linear or random disturbance driven filtered signals, etc. and the trend type is normally unknown. To remove the unknown trend, a low-pass trend filter can be used to estimate the trend signal. The filtfilt function applies a linear digital filter twice, once forward and once backwards. The combined filter has zero phase and a filter order twice that of the original.\n",
    "\n",
    "It should be aware that A <b>Too small TTSS value for a case may lead to an “over-detrending” </b>that may remove useful dynamic information from the data and cause inaccurate models. If users do want to see models with short TTSS, they can manually change the detrending filter TTSS, to avoid the negative impacts of a too-short TTSS."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create FIR filter to detrend signal\n",
    "tags = inputs + outputs\n",
    "tss = 120\n",
    "filter_tss_mult_factor = 3\n",
    "d_filter = FilterFactory.create('highpass')\n",
    "d_filter.apply_filter(slice1[tags], tss, filter_tss_mult_factor)\n",
    "idinput = d_filter.data_manager.get_data(\"output\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
